Concrete Strength Prediction

Summary:¶

Using the data collected from existing customers, build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

 

Attribute Information:¶

Given are the variable name, variable type, the measurement unit, and a brief description. The concrete compressive strength is the regression problem. The order of this listing corresponds to the order of numerals along the rows of the database.

  • Cement - kg in a m3 mixture (input variable)
  • Blast Furnace Slag - kg in a m3 mixture (input variable)
  • Fly Ash - kg in a m3 mixture (input variable)
  • Water - kg in a m3 mixture (input variable)
  • Superplasticizer - kg in a m3 mixture (input variable)
  • Coarse Aggregate - kg in a m3 mixture (input variable)
  • Fine Aggregate - kg in a m3 mixture (input variable)
  • Age - day (1 - 365) (input variable)
  • Concrete compressive strength - MPa (output variable)

 

Objective:¶

To predict the concrete strength using the data available in file "concrete.csv". Apply feature engineering and model tuning to obtain 85% to 95% accuracy.

Brandon Smith

10/17/2020

7. Prepare and Split Data¶

In [35]:
#make copy of the data for working with to prevent altering 
prepared_concrete_data = concrete_data.copy()
In [36]:
#split into X & y
X = prepared_concrete_data.drop("strength" , axis=1)
y = prepared_concrete_data['strength']
In [37]:
#split the training data and test data at 70% / 30%
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=.3, random_state=7)
In [38]:
#split the test data into the test data and vaidation data at .5 so 15% each of the total dataset size
X_test, X_valid, y_test, y_valid = train_test_split(X_test, y_test, test_size=.5, random_state=7)

Variables¶

In [119]:
#Declare variables for KFOld work below
foldCount = 50
randomState = 7
estimatorCount = 50
kfold = KFold(n_splits=foldCount, random_state=randomState, shuffle=True)

#Create a results dataframe to store the needed results
modelKfold_results_data = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model','Accuracy Mean','Accuracy Standard','Score','Notes'])

Functions¶

In [148]:
#Create function for analytics (can pass in test or validation data)
def getMetrics(model, xTest,yTest,xTrain,yTrain):
    yMean = yTrain.mean()
    sst = ((yTrain - yMean)**2).sum()
    sse = ((yTrain - model.predict(xTrain))**2).sum()
    rSquared = 1- sse/sst
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(yTest,model.predict(xTest)))
    return rSquared, rmse, sse, sst

{'bootstrap': True, 'max_features': 7, 'max_samples': 6, 'n_estimators': 40}
